 As far as Japanese programs go, there isn't many that start from scratch (at least that do a decent job), like you want and need. If you want to teach yourself because there's no schools/universities that offer Japanese language classes, you may have to shell out some cash to buy a few books. Starnova's links have good resources, though.<br>
<br>
There's also:<br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://rut.org/cgi-bin/j-e/dict">rut.org/cgi-bin/j-e/dict</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://jin.jcic.or.jp/kidsweb/language.html">jin.jcic.or.jp/kidsweb/language.html</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.japanese-online.com/LANGUAGE/index.htm">www.japanese-online.com/L.../index.htm</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.mlcjapanese.co.jp/Download.htm">www.mlcjapanese.co.jp/Download.htm</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
If none of those do it for you, go to www.google.com and type in &quot;Japanese lessons,&quot; &quot;Japanese language tutorials,&quot; etc... You get the idea. Just make sure that they have audio files you can listen to. It's completely different reading it and hearing it; writing it and speaking it. Remember to get your pronunciation down before anything else.  <br>
<br>
 There's a book on grammar:<br>
 <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/tg/detail/-/0812046439/qid=1044659348/sr=8-2/ref=sr_8_2/103-7026905-7555035?v=glance&s=books&n=507846">www.amazon.com/exec/obido...s&n=507846</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
 It's just a tiny pocketbook, but it's probably the best I've seen for explaining Japanese grammar (oh, how it confuses my slow brain!). The rest you MAY be able to pick up off the internet. <br>
<br>
If you have any questions at all, just post them on here. There's quite a few knowlegable people (save myself) around here. <br>
<br>
Yeah. Hopefully that helped.<br>
